    "body": "<span class=\"solution-visible-txt\">All submissions for this problem are available.</span><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Cisco is out of his senses and needs some refreshment. So he decided to solve a puzzle given by Detective Joe. Joe gave him <b>4</b> boxes having different colour of balls having red balls in box 1 , blue in box 2 , green in box 3 and white in box 4 .<p> Let count of balls in red box be <b>R</b> , in blue be <b>B</b> , in green be <b>G</b> and in white be <b>W</b> . Joe then mark all the red balls with integers from 1 to <b>R</b> , similarly he marks all blue balls from 1 to <b>B</b> , green balls from 1 to <b>G</b> and white balls from 1 to <b>W</b>.</p> Now he told Cisco to count the number of ways in which he can arrange all the balls in straight line such that no two balls with same number are adjacent to each other .\n</p><br>\n\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n\n\n<h3>Input</h3>\n<p>\nThe first line of the input contains an integer <b>T</b> denoting the number of test cases. The description of <b>T</b> test cases as follows.<br>\nThe first line of the test case consist of four integers <b>R</b> , <b>G</b>, <b>B</b> and <b>W</b>. \n</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n\n<h3>Output</h3>\n<p>\nPrint a single line containing the number of ways to arrange the balls in straight path.As the answer could be large output it <b>modulo 1000000007</b>\n</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n\n<h3>Constraints</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><b>1</b> \u2264 <b>T</b> \u2264 <b> 100</b></li>\n<br>\n<li><b>0</b> \u2264 <b>R</b> \u2264 <b> 12</b></li><br>\n<li><b>0</b> \u2264 <b>G</b> \u2264 <b> 12</b></li><br>\n<li><b>0</b> \u2264 <b>B</b> \u2264 <b> 12</b></li><br>\n<li><b>0</b> \u2264 <b>W</b> \u2264 <b> 12</b></li><br>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<h3>Example</h3>\n<pre><b>Input:</b>\n3\n1 1 1 1\n1 2 0 0\n1 3 0 0\n\n<b>Output:</b>\n0\n2\n12\n</pre>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<h3>Explanation</h3>\n<p><b>Example case 1.</b>In this there is no ways to arrange the balls as they have same number written on them</p>\n<p><b>Example case 2.</b>In this there is only two ways to do it (1R,2G,1G) and (1G,2G,1R)\nwhere 1R represents red ball numbered 1.</p>",
